  "prompt": "How much workout to do in a day to lose 25 kgs in 1 month?",
  "response": "Losing **25 kg (55 lbs) in one month** is an extremely aggressive and unhealthy goal. A safe and sustainable weight loss rate is typically **0.5 to 1 kg (1 to 2 lbs) per week**, which means losing 25 kg would realistically take **6 months to a year** depending on your starting weight, diet, and lifestyle.\n\nAttempting to lose weight at such a rapid pace can lead to serious health risks, including:\n- Muscle loss\n- Nutritional deficiencies\n- Gallstones\n- A weakened immune system\n- Hormonal imbalances\n\n### If you still want to aim for significant weight loss, here\u2019s a more balanced and sustainable approach:\n\n#### 1. **Calorie Deficit**\n   - Create a calorie deficit of **500\u20131000 calories per day** to lose **0.5\u20131 kg per week**.\n   - Use a calorie calculator to determine your daily maintenance calories and subtract the deficit.\n\n#### 2. **Exercise Plan**\n   - Combine **cardio** and **strength training** for optimal results.\n   - **Cardio:** Aim for **45\u201360 minutes** of moderate-intensity cardio (e.g., running, cycling, swimming) **5\u20136 days a week**.\n   - **Strength Training:** Do full-body strength training **3\u20134 days a week** to preserve muscle mass and boost metabolism.\n\n#### 3. **Diet**\n   - Focus on a **high-protein, low-calorie diet** with plenty of vegetables, lean proteins, and whole grains.\n   - Avoid sugary drinks, processed foods, and excessive carbs.\n   - Stay hydrated by drinking at least **2\u20133 liters of water daily**.\n\n#### 4. **Rest and Recovery**\n   - Get **7\u20139 hours of sleep** per night to support recovery and hormone regulation.\n   - Avoid overtraining to prevent burnout or injury.\n\n#### 5. **Consult a Professional**\n   - Work with a doctor, dietitian, or certified trainer to create a personalized plan tailored to your needs and health status.\n\n### Final Note:\nRapid weight loss is not sustainable and can harm your health. Aim for gradual, healthy changes that you can maintain long-term. Remember, weight loss is a marathon, not a sprint.",
